cs.AI, cs.LG, cs.CV, cs.GT, cs.GR

The paper proposes a method for addressing the problem of incomplete information in the game of StarCraft, which is a popular environment for artificial intelligence research. The proposed method involves using a convolutional encoder-decoder architecture to predict potential counts and locations of the opponent's units based on only partially visible and noisy information. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the sub-categories of cs.AI (artificial intelligence), cs.LG (machine learning), and cs.CV (computer vision), which are all relevant to the proposed method. Additionally, the paper evaluates the performance of the proposed method by training a classifier to predict the game outcome, which suggests that it may also belong to the sub-categories of cs.GT (game theory) and cs.GR (graphics).
